findings.description:
--- code begin (reference only) ---
await execAsync(`git rev-parse --verify "${branchName}"`, { cwd: workingDir });
await execAsync(`git rev-parse "${ref}"`, { cwd: workingDir });
await execAsync(`git remote get-url "${remoteName}"`, { cwd: workingDir });
await execAsync(`git checkout "${baseBranch}"`, { cwd: config.workingDir });
await execAsync(`git checkout -b "${branchName}"`, { cwd: config.workingDir });
await execAsync(`git push -u "${remoteName}" "${branchName}"`, { cwd: config.workingDir });
--- code end ---

All six git operations in branchManager.ts use exec() (which spawns a shell) with template literals that embed variable data directly into the shell command string. Although double-quotes are included around each variable, a value containing an embedded double-quote followed by shell metacharacters (e.g. a branch name like `foo" && rm -rf /`) can escape the quoting and inject arbitrary shell commands. The branchName comes from external inputs (featureId passed through generateBranchName, or caller-supplied branchName/baseBranch). The remote name (remoteName) is caller-controlled. validateBranchName blocks spaces and some metacharacters, but it does NOT block embedded double-quotes, backticks, or dollar signs, which are sufficient for injection. In contrast, the patchManager already uses execFile() with an argv array for git apply. The branchManager must be migrated to the same pattern.

--- code begin (reference only) ---
const commitMessage = `${message}\n\n[task_id: ${taskId}]\n[feature_id: ${config.featureId}]`;
await execAsync(`git commit -m "${commitMessage.replace(/"/g, '\\"')}"`, {
  cwd: config.workingDir,
});
--- code end ---

The commit message is composed from three separate inputs—message (caller-supplied), taskId (caller-supplied), and config.featureId—and then embedded into a shell command string using exec(). The only sanitization applied is escaping double-quote characters. A message or taskId containing a backtick, $(), or newline followed by shell commands can still escape the quoting context. For example, a taskId of `foo\n" && malicious_cmd #` would terminate the -m argument early. No validation is applied to message or taskId values before they are embedded. The fix is to use execFileAsync('git', ['commit', '-m', commitMessage]) which passes the message as a single argv element with no shell interpretation.

--- code begin (reference only) ---
await execAsync('git symbolic-ref -q HEAD || git rev-parse HEAD', {
  cwd: workingDir,
});
--- code end ---

This single call to exec() intentionally uses a shell pipeline (|| operator) to fall back from git symbolic-ref to git rev-parse. Since exec() spawns a shell, the command string is interpreted by /bin/sh. While the static string itself is not user-controlled, the use of exec() for shell features (instead of execFile) in the same file that otherwise uses execFileAsync for other git operations is an inconsistency that establishes a dangerous pattern. More critically, if workingDir were ever interpolated here (it is not currently), this would be an immediate injection. The shell is not needed: these two commands can be called sequentially with execFileAsync, and the fallback can be implemented in application logic.

--- code begin (reference only) ---
// src/telemetry/rateLimitLedger.ts:130
return JSON.parse(content) as RateLimitLedgerData;

// src/telemetry/costTracker.ts:533
const state = JSON.parse(content) as CostTrackerState;

// src/cli/utils/writeActionQueueReporter.ts:122
const manifest = JSON.parse(manifestContent) as WriteActionQueueManifest;

// src/workflows/writeActionQueue.ts:657
return JSON.parse(content) as WriteActionQueueManifest;

// src/workflows/contextSummarizer.ts:357
return JSON.parse(content) as ChunkMetadata;

// src/workflows/deployment/context.ts:87
pr = JSON.parse(prContent) as PRMetadata;

// src/workflows/resumeCoordinator.ts:747 and resumeQueueRecovery.ts:58
const rawSnapshot = JSON.parse(content) as { ... };

// src/workflows/branchProtectionReporter.ts:241
const commandsData = JSON.parse(commandsContent) as { commands?: ... };

// src/workflows/approvalRegistry.ts:420
const parsed = JSON.parse(content) as ApprovalsFile;
--- code end ---

These call sites load JSON from run-directory files using TypeScript `as` casts instead of Zod schema validation. The cast is a compile-time fiction: at runtime the parsed value is `unknown` and receives no structural validation. If a run-directory file is corrupted, externally modified, or injected by a TOCTOU attack, downstream code will process malformed data as if it were the expected type. This can cause undefined property accesses, incorrect business logic, or silent data corruption in telemetry and cost tracking. Compare to the safe pattern already used in the same codebase (queueStore.ts:376, branchManager.ts, linearAdapter.ts, specComposer.ts, taskPlanner.ts) which passes JSON.parse output through validateOrThrow() before use.

--- code begin (reference only) ---
// validatePatchDryRun (line 424)
const patchFile = path.join('/tmp', `patch-${patch.patchId}-${Date.now()}.diff`);
await fs.writeFile(patchFile, patch.content, 'utf-8');
await execFileAsync('git', ['apply', '--check', patchFile], { cwd: workingDir });

// applyPatch (line 641)
const patchFile = path.join('/tmp', `patch-${patch.patchId}-${Date.now()}.diff`);
await fs.writeFile(patchFile, patch.content, 'utf-8');
await execFileAsync('git', ['apply', patchFile], { cwd: config.workingDir });
--- code end ---

Patch content (unified diffs that modify repository source files) is written to /tmp using a predictable filename pattern: `patch-<patchId>-<timestamp>.diff`. The patchId is validated to alphanumeric/dot/hyphen, and a timestamp adds ~millisecond entropy, but on a shared system:
1. A symlink attack could redirect the write to an arbitrary path (TOCTOU between writeFile and git apply).
2. Other users on the system can read, modify, or replace the patch file between writeFile and git apply --check/apply, potentially causing git to apply a malicious diff.
3. The file is written without explicit permissions, defaulting to umask-derived permissions (typically 0644), making it world-readable.

The cleanup in the finally block reduces exposure window but does not eliminate the race.

--- code begin (reference only) ---
// src/adapters/http/client.ts:625
return (await response.json()) as T;

// src/adapters/http/client.ts:635
return JSON.parse(text) as T;
--- code end ---

The HttpClient.parseResponseBody method casts parsed API responses directly to the caller's generic type T without any runtime schema validation. API responses from external services (GitHub, Linear, agent providers) may differ from expected types due to API version changes, error conditions that return unexpected shapes, or malicious/compromised upstream services. Downstream callers (GitHubAdapter, LinearAdapter) then access properties on the cast result without nil-checks, which can produce silent incorrect behavior or runtime TypeErrors that surface as unhandled rejections. The adapter layer is a critical trust boundary where external untrusted data enters the system.

--- code begin (reference only) ---
// approvalRegistry.ts loadApprovalsFile()
const content = await fs.readFile(approvalsPath, 'utf-8');
const parsed = JSON.parse(content) as ApprovalsFile;

// Validation only checks schema_version string:
if (parsed.schema_version !== APPROVALS_SCHEMA_VERSION) {
  throw new Error(`Approvals file schema version mismatch: ...`);
}
return parsed;
--- code end ---

The approvals system controls whether PRD and plan gates are considered approved for pipeline progression. The loadApprovalsFile function deserializes approval records from disk using an unsafe type cast. The only structural check is a schema_version string comparison. If an approvals.json file is corrupted or contains a crafted payload with schema_version set to the expected value but otherwise malformed approval data (wrong gate_type, missing required fields, injected featureId), downstream approval checks will operate on unvalidated data. This is a security-relevant code path—incorrect approval state can allow unauthorized pipeline progression through governance gates.

--- code begin (reference only) ---
// src/workflows/deployment/context.ts:87
const prContent = await fs.readFile(prJsonPath, 'utf-8');
pr = JSON.parse(prContent) as PRMetadata;
logger.debug('Loaded PR metadata', { pr_number: pr.pr_number, branch: pr.branch });
--- code end ---

PR metadata (pr.json) is loaded from the run directory with a bare type cast and no structural validation. This metadata drives subsequent deployment and auto-merge decisions including PR number lookup, branch identification, and merge strategy selection. A malformed or externally-tampered pr.json could cause deployment operations to target the wrong PR or branch. The PRMetadata type is defined (src/core/models/prMetadata.ts) but no Zod schema is used at this load boundary.

--- code begin (reference only) ---
// src/telemetry/costTracker.ts:533
const state = JSON.parse(content) as CostTrackerState;
const tracker = new CostTracker(state.feature_id, runDir, logger, metrics, state.budget);
tracker.state = state;

// src/telemetry/rateLimitLedger.ts:130
return JSON.parse(content) as RateLimitLedgerData;
--- code end ---

The cost tracker and rate limit ledger restore their internal state from JSON files using bare type casts. CostTrackerState contains financial data (total cost in USD, token counts, budget limits). If the persisted file contains manipulated values (e.g. an inflated budget, zeroed cost totals, or incorrect token counts), the tracker will operate with incorrect state for the entire pipeline run. Rate limit ledger tampering could cause the system to exceed API rate limits by believing it has more headroom than it does. These files are written by the pipeline itself, but their integrity is not verified on load.

--- code begin (reference only) ---
// src/workflows/writeActionQueue.ts:602
const action = JSON.parse(line) as WriteAction;
actions.set(action.action_id, action);

// src/workflows/writeActionQueue.ts:657
return JSON.parse(content) as WriteActionQueueManifest;

// src/cli/utils/writeActionQueueReporter.ts:122
const manifest = JSON.parse(manifestContent) as WriteActionQueueManifest;
--- code end ---

The write-action queue stores actions that drive file writes and code modifications. Individual action lines are deserialized with a bare cast and the action_id is used immediately as a Map key and for downstream routing without validation. The queue manifest (which tracks counts and checksums) is similarly unvalidated. A corrupted or injected queue entry could cause write operations to be attributed to the wrong action_id or miss required fields that drive conditional logic.

--- code begin (reference only) ---
// src/workflows/contextSummarizer.ts:357
return JSON.parse(content) as ChunkMetadata;
--- code end ---

ChunkMetadata is loaded from a file in the run directory and used to drive context summarization decisions (which chunks to include, token counts, etc.). The type cast bypasses any structural validation. If the metadata file is malformed, incorrect token counts or chunk boundaries could cause the summarizer to exceed token budgets or produce incorrect summaries passed to the agent.

--- code begin (reference only) ---
await execAsync('git symbolic-ref -q HEAD || git rev-parse HEAD', {
  cwd: workingDir,
});
--- code end ---

The execAsync function wraps Node.js exec(), which invokes the system shell to interpret the command string. This call deliberately uses a shell pipeline (`||` operator). While the command string itself is a static literal with no interpolated variables, this establishes a precedent for shell usage in a module where all other git operations now use execFileAsync (which does not invoke a shell). If this pattern is later extended or copied by a developer who adds variable interpolation, it becomes an injection vector. Additionally, the shell adds unnecessary attack surface and portability concerns (shell path, shell version differences).

--- code begin (reference only) ---
// src/workflows/branchProtectionReporter.ts:241
const commandsData = JSON.parse(commandsContent) as {
  commands?: Array<{ type: string; description?: string }>;
};
if (commandsData.commands) {
  registryContexts = commandsData.commands.map((cmd) => `validation/${cmd.type}`);
}
--- code end ---

Validation command types from commands.json are mapped to GitHub check context names by string concatenation. If commands.json contains a crafted type value containing path-separator characters or special characters (e.g. `../../secrets` or a value with GitHub check context injection patterns), the resulting context string could match unintended branch protection rules. No schema validation or sanitization of the type field is performed before string construction.

--- code begin (reference only) ---
// src/workflows/resumeCoordinator.ts:747
const rawSnapshot = JSON.parse(content) as {
  schemaVersion?: string;
  schema_version?: string;
  tasks: { [taskId: string]: unknown };
  counts?: unknown;
  dependencyGraph?: Record<string, string[]>;
  dependency_graph?: Record<string, string[]>;
  checksum: string;
  timestamp: string;
};

// src/workflows/resumeQueueRecovery.ts:58
const rawSnapshot = JSON.parse(content) as { ... };
--- code end ---

The queue snapshot is used for resume operations—reconstructing task state after a pipeline restart. Both files cast the parsed JSON without structural validation. The checksum field is compared for integrity, but only after trusting the parsed type (if the checksum field itself is missing from a malformed file, accessing rawSnapshot.checksum silently produces undefined, causing the integrity check to pass vacuously). The tasks dictionary is iterated directly from the cast object. Missing or extra fields on task objects can cause incorrect resume behavior.

--- code begin (reference only) ---
// src/workflows/contextAggregator.ts:165
const config: AggregatorConfig = {
  repoRoot: path.dirname(path.resolve(process.cwd(), '.codemachine.yml')),
  ...
};
--- code end ---

The repoRoot is derived by taking the dirname of a config file resolved relative to process.cwd(). If process.cwd() is not a git repository root (e.g. if the CLI is invoked from a subdirectory), the derived repoRoot may be incorrect but will still be used to scan the filesystem. Subsequent directory traversal in discoverFiles() will recursively read from this root. There is no check that repoRoot is within the git repository boundary (no call to git rev-parse --show-toplevel to verify). On misconfiguration, the aggregator could scan directories outside the intended repository, potentially including parent directories with sensitive files.

--- code begin (reference only) ---
async function scanDirectory(dir: string): Promise<void> {
  const entries = await fs.readdir(dir, { withFileTypes: true });
  for (const entry of entries) {
    const fullPath = path.join(dir, entry.name);
    if (entry.isDirectory()) {
      await scanDirectory(fullPath); // recurse
    } else if (entry.isFile()) {
      discovered.add(fullPath);
    }
  }
}
--- code end ---

The discoverFiles function uses readdir with withFileTypes to identify directories and files, but does not check entry.isSymbolicLink(). On Linux/macOS, entry.isDirectory() and entry.isFile() return true for symlinks pointing to directories and files respectively (the check follows the symlink). A symlink within the repository pointing outside the repository root (e.g. /etc, /home/user/.ssh) would be followed during the recursive scan, and files from outside the boundary would be included in the context document sent to the agent. The debt-conventions skill explicitly requires: 'Skip symlinks to locations outside project'.

--- code begin (reference only) ---
// src/workflows/specComposer.ts:755
JSON.parse(metadataContent),  // passed to validateOrThrow - OK

// src/workflows/specComposer.ts:833
JSON.parse(existingIndex),    // no schema - cast

// src/workflows/specComposer.ts:877
JSON.parse(content),          // passed to validateOrThrow - OK
--- code end ---

Line 833 in specComposer.ts loads an existing spec index via JSON.parse without applying a Zod schema, while the adjacent calls at lines 755 and 877 correctly use validateOrThrow. The inconsistency means the spec index (which drives section inclusion/exclusion decisions in PRD authoring) can contain unexpected structure that propagates into the authoring engine.

--- code begin (reference only) ---
// src/workflows/taskPlanner.ts:211
specJson = JSON.parse(specContent);

// Used as:
const spec = specJson as {
  test_plan?: Array<{ test_id: string; description: string; ... }>;
};
if (spec.test_plan && Array.isArray(spec.test_plan)) {
  for (const test of spec.test_plan) {
    ...
    requirements.push({
      id: test.test_id,
      description: test.description,
    });
  }
}
--- code end ---

The spec.json is loaded from the run artifacts directory and cast without Zod validation. Individual test entries are accessed directly. While there is an Array.isArray guard, individual test fields (test_id, description) are accessed without type-checking. A malformed spec could produce undefined test_ids that propagate into task planning, potentially causing task deduplication or dependency resolution to behave incorrectly.

--- code begin (reference only) ---
// src/workflows/writeActionQueue.ts:600-606
for (const line of lines) {
  try {
    const action = JSON.parse(line) as WriteAction;
    actions.set(action.action_id, action);
  } catch {
    // Skip corrupted lines
  }
}
--- code end ---

Corrupted lines in the JSONL queue file are silently dropped with no logging or metric increment. This means queue corruption (whether from disk errors, concurrent writes, or malicious tampering) is invisible to operators. A partially-corrupted queue could result in actions being silently lost without any observable signal, causing pipeline runs to complete without executing all required write actions.

--- code begin (reference only) ---
// src/workflows/patchManager.ts:424
const patchFile = path.join('/tmp', `patch-${patch.patchId}-${Date.now()}.diff`);

// src/workflows/patchManager.ts:641
const patchFile = path.join('/tmp', `patch-${patch.patchId}-${Date.now()}.diff`);
--- code end ---

The path /tmp is hardcoded in two locations. On Windows (which the package.json and PLATFORM_MAP indicate is a supported platform via win32-x64), /tmp may not exist. The CLAUDE.md also documents that the CLI targets Node >= 24. The correct cross-platform API is os.tmpdir(). While this is primarily a reliability issue, using os.tmpdir() also ensures the temp directory respects OS-level security settings and is on the same filesystem as the patch content, reducing symlink attack risk.
